We now prepare the data for plotting!

A simple way to visualize the nature of the steps taken is through Histograms. The first histogram shows the range with the highest number of steps taken each day while the second histogram shows the average number of steps taken a day

par( mfrow = c(1,2))
hist(y$steps, xlab = "Daily Steps", main = "Sum of Daily Steps", col = "orange" )
hist(means$steps, xlab = "Mean Steps 5 minute per period", main = "Means of Daily Steps")

In most cases the user take between 10 000 and 15 000 steps a day and on average 30 to 40 steps per 5 minute interval

Now let us see if there is a difference between what happen during the week and on weekends

readings$days<-weekdays(readings$date)
days<- c("Monday" ,"Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday")
weekends<- c("Saturday", "Sunday")

daysteps     <- readings[which(readings[,"days"] %in% days), ]
weekendsteps <- readings[which(readings[,"days"] %in% weekends),]

intervals_weekdays <- aggregate(steps~interval, daysteps , sum)
intervals_weekends <- aggregate(steps~interval, weekendsteps , sum)

library(lattice)

xyplot(steps~interval, data = intervals_weekdays, type = "l", main = "Weekdays") 

xyplot(steps~interval, data = intervals_weekends, type = "l", main = "Weekends")
